Here's a practical approach:

## 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create a `ResourceDictionary` for each theme:

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with appropriate values.

## 2. Merge a default theme in `App.xaml`

```xml
<Application.Resources>
    <ResourceDictionary>
        <ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries>
            <ResourceDictionary Source="Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml" />
        </ResourceDictionary.MergedDictionaries>
    </ResourceDictionary>
</Application.Resources>
```

## 3. Reference keys with `DynamicResource`

Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so changes propagate at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 4. Switch themes at runtime

```csharp
public static class ThemeManager
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        var source = theme switch
        {
            "Dark"         => "Resources/Styles/DarkTheme.xaml",
            "HighContrast" => "Resources/Styles/HighContrastTheme.xaml",
            _              => "Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml"
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(new ResourceDictionary { Source = new Uri(source, UriKind.Relative) });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme);
    }
}
```

## 5. Settings page picker

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    public SettingsPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        themePicker.SelectedItem = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    }

    void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        if (themePicker.SelectedItem is string selected)
            ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(selected);
    }
}
```

## 6. Restore on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

**Key points:**
- `DynamicResource` is essential — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- Keep the same keys across all three dictionaries so lookups never miss.
- `Preferences` (from MAUI Essentials) persists the user's choice across launches.
